        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(qmd): preserve Windows absolute paths in command resolution",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nFix #92302 — `memory.qmd.command` path mangled on Windows, making QMD memory backend unusable on Windows despite working CLI.\n\n`splitShellArgs` treats `\\` as a POSIX shell escape character. When the configured QMD command is a Windows absolute path (e.g., `C:\\Users\\...\\qmd.js`), every backslash is consumed as an escape, stripping path separators and producing an unspawnable command.\n\nThis fix adds `isWindowsAbsoluteCommandPath()` to detect drive-letter (`C:\\...`) and UNC (`\\\\server\\...`) paths, and `extractQmdCommandToken()` to extract the command token by splitting on the first space instead of going through `splitShellArgs` for Windows paths.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `packages/memory-host-sdk/src/host/backend-config.ts` — add `isWindowsAbsoluteCommandPath()` and `extractQmdCommandToken()` helpers; use `extractQmdCommandToken` instead of inline `splitShellArgs` in `resolveMemoryBackendConfig`\n- `packages/memory-host-sdk/src/host/backend-config.test.ts` — add regression tests for Windows drive-letter and UNC paths\n\n## Verification\n\n- All 28 tests pass (26 existing + 2 new Windows path tests)\n- `pnpm test packages/memory-host-sdk/src/host/backend-config.test.ts` ✓\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed:** `splitShellArgs` consumes every `\\` as a POSIX shell escape outside quotes, mangling Windows absolute paths into unspawnable strings.\n\n**Real environment tested:** Node.js 22.22.0, Linux x64 (string parsing is platform-independent; the bug and fix are pure string logic).\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n1. Construct a Windows absolute path as configured in `openclaw.json`: `C:\\Users\\user\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\@tobilu\\qmd\\dist\\cli\\qmd.js`\n2. Pass it through `splitShellArgs` directly (before fix)\n3. Pass it through `extractQmdCommandToken` (after fix)\n4. Verify the POSIX quoted path fallback still works\n\n**Evidence after fix:**\n\n```\n=== BEFORE fix (splitShellArgs directly) ===\nInput:  C:\\Users\\user\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\@tobilu\\qmd\\dist\\cli\\qmd.js\nOutput: C:UsersuserAppDataRoamingnpmnode_modules@tobiluqmddistcliqmd.js\nResult: PATH MANGLED — backslashes stripped, unspawnable\n\n=== AFTER fix (extractQmdCommandToken) ===\nInput:  C:\\Users\\user\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\@tobilu\\qmd\\dist\\cli\\qmd.js\nOutput: C:\\Users\\user\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\@tobilu\\qmd\\dist\\cli\\qmd.js\nResult: PATH PRESERVED — spawnable\n\n=== POSIX path still works ===\nInput:  \"/Applications/QMD Tools/qmd\" --flag\nOutput: /Applications/QMD Tools/qmd\n```\n\n**Observed result after fix:** Windows absolute paths (drive-letter and UNC) are preserved intact. POSIX quoted paths continue to work through `splitShellArgs` as before.\n\n**What was not tested:** Real Windows spawn of `qmd.js` with this exact config — requires a Windows 11 machine with `@tobilu/qmd` installed. The original reporter's environment (`openclaw/openclaw#92302`) provides real-world Windows confirmation. The fix changes only string tokenization; the downstream spawn path through `resolveWindowsSpawnProgram` / `materializeWindowsSpawnProgram` is unchanged.\n\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)",
